<h1>Adverbs of Degree</h1>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{totemo}}</strong> is an adverb that precedes the adjective it is modifying. It is used in affirmative sentences
to mean "very".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{pekinn}}ha<strong>totemo</strong>@KJ{{cold}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Beijing is very cold.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{amari}}</strong> is an adverb that precedes the adjective it is modifying. It is used in negative sentences
to mean "not very".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{sakura@KJ{{large^study}}ha<strong>amari</strong>@KJ{{possess^name}}na@KJ{{large^study}}jaarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Sakura Univeristy is not a very famous university.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

